  "prompt": "What is the process to sue a mobile services company (T-Mobile in my case) for false charges? And, how long is it going to take for the claim to be addressed?",
  "response": "To sue T-Mobile for false charges, follow these steps:\n\n1. Preliminary Actions:\n- Document all false charges\n- Gather evidence (billing statements, communication records)\n- File a formal complaint with T-Mobile customer service\n- Request a detailed investigation\n- Keep records of all communications\n\n2. Legal Options:\na) Small Claims Court\n- Suitable for claims under $10,000\n- Lower filing fees\n- No lawyer typically required\n- Faster resolution (2-3 months)\n- Filing fees vary by state ($30-$100)\n\nb) Civil Lawsuit\n- Better for larger amounts\n- Requires hiring an attorney\n- More complex process\n- Potentially longer resolution (6-18 months)\n- Higher legal costs\n\n3. Potential Preliminary Alternatives:\n- Consumer Protection Bureau complaint\n- Better Business Bureau complaint\n- State Attorney General's office complaint\n\n4. Lawsuit Process Timeline:\n- Initial filing: 1-2 weeks\n- Court processing: 1-3 months\n- Potential mediation/settlement: 2-6 months\n- Full trial (if necessary): 6-18 months\n\nRecommended initial steps:\n1. Document everything\n2. Contact T-Mobile customer service\n3. File formal written complaint\n4. Consult local legal resources/attorney",
